  • Accuracy: Looking for outliers using box plots
In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

numerical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['number'])
fig,axs = plt.subplots(ncols=len(numerical_columns.columns), figsize=(40, 10))
for i in range(len(numerical_columns.columns)):
    sns.boxplot(x=numerical_columns.columns[i], data=numerical_columns, ax=axs[i])
plt.show()

From above, we see only one outlier in Life ladder and log GDP per capita and hence, mostly accurate data whereas numerous outliers in social support(sparsely placed), healthy life expectancy plan(some closely and some at distant),freedom to make life choices (dense), generosity (dense), corruption (extreme dense) which remarks that data for these features is not too accurate. Looks like corruption outliers are maximum. Also, positive effect has less outliers than negative effect. Conclusion: The features like corruption, freedom to make choices, social support or genrosity have too many outliers. This is somehow indicating that they just not might be outliers but probably a category of data which is not correctly represented from boxplots.

In [7]:
fig,axs = plt.subplots(ncols=len(numerical_columns.columns), figsize=(35, 10))
for i in range(len(numerical_columns.columns)):
    sns.histplot(x=numerical_columns.columns[i], data=numerical_columns, ax=axs[i], kde=True)
plt.show()

From the above graphs, we observed that following have:¶

  • Normal Distribution curve

    • year
    • Life Ladder
      • Analysis: Most people from the dataset shows more than average rate of life ladder (best possible life for you) which is lifeLadder > 4.5
    • Log GDP per Capita
      • Analysis:Most people live in countries where log GDP per capita > 9.This is as expected from human tendency to live where GDP is high.
    • Generosity
    • Positive Effect

    • Negative effect

      • Both Positive and negative effect, we see people having maximun positive effect are equal to number of people having maximum negative effect

  • Power-Law Distribution curve

    • Social Support
    • Healthy Life expectancy at birth
    • Freedom to make life choices

    • Perception of corruption

      • Analysis:We observe that social support, life expectancy and freedom to make choices are quite high than. expected. For perceptions of corruption, the count of number of people is also higher

In [9]:
sns.heatmap(numerical_columns.corr(), annot = True)
Out[9]:
<Axes: >

Analysis: Following are the observations:

  • The heatmap shows that happier people (high life ladder score) are living in countries with high log GDP per capita, better social support and healthy life expectancy at birth.
  • We see a strong correlation between high expectancy at birth and Log GDP per capita, that is, countries with High GDP per capita have good healthy life expectancy at birth.
  • We see that generosity in people has negligible relationship to Log GDP per capita of the country which is expected.
  • It is seen that countries with higher corruption are negatively correlated with life ladder/happiness score meaning that countries with higher corruption have lower happiness scores.

happiest_Country_22 = df_2022.loc[df_2022['Life Ladder'].idxmax()]['Country name']
print("Happiest country in 2022: ", happiest_Country_22)

Happiest country in 2022:  Finland

Of the countries in this dataset, which country had the largest increase in happiness from its start of participation to 2023?

In [23]:
df['Happiness Increase'] = df['Life Ladder'] - df.groupby('Country name')['Life Ladder'].transform('first')
df['Last Happiness Increase'] = df.groupby('Country name')['Happiness Increase'].transform('last')
print("Country with highest happiness increase: ", df.loc[df['Last Happiness Increase'].idxmax()]['Country name'])

Country with highest happiness increase:  Congo (Brazzaville)

Which had the largest decrease in happiness?

In [18]:
print("Country with least happiness increase: ", df.loc[df['Last Happiness Increase'].idxmin()]['Country name'])

Country with least happiness increase:  Lebanon

Assumptions:¶

  • Life Ladder (best possible life score) is equivalent to happiness score ranes from 0 to 10.
  • Social support is the support given by government in terms of monetary funds.
  • Genrosity is the money donated to charity inpast month on GDP per capita.
  • Countries that exist in the universe are all present in the dataset.
  • In calculating largest/least increase in happiness, made an assumption of calculating from 2023 and country's earliest year entry.
